WEBVTT

1
00:00:22.766 --> 00:00:24.100
There'll always be
the argument

2
00:00:24.133 --> 00:00:26.702
that video games
are meant to be played for fun.

3
00:00:27.933 --> 00:00:30.402
Believe me.
some of it's a lot of fun.

4
00:00:30.433 --> 00:00:33.068
Video games are meant
to be played at home.

5
00:00:33.100 --> 00:00:36.770
relaxing on a couch
amongst friends.

6
00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:39.302
And they are. and that's fun.

7
00:00:39.333 --> 00:00:41.234
But competitive gaming.

8
00:00:41.266 --> 00:00:44.068
when you wanna attach
your name to a world record.

9
00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:46.936
when you want your name
written into history.

10
00:00:46.966 --> 00:00:48.167
you have to pay the price.

11
00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:50.402
With this. it's just
like me and the machine.

12
00:00:50.433 --> 00:00:55.437
l can--lt doesn't matter if you.
you know--lf you let me down

13
00:00:55.466 --> 00:00:58.202
or someone else.
it doesn't come through.

14
00:00:58.233 --> 00:01:01.102
l can always go out there.
l'm in control.

15
00:01:15.133 --> 00:01:16.334
And l'm glad
you touch on this.

16
00:01:16.366 --> 00:01:17.834
Do we have enough tape?
This is important.

17
00:01:19.066 --> 00:01:21.435
Everybody. even Grandma.

18
00:01:21.466 --> 00:01:26.938
games--meaning checkers. cards.
if not now. in the past.

19
00:01:26.966 --> 00:01:28.967
Show me even
a freakin' nun or a hermit

20
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:30.668
who hasn't done cards
or checkers.

21
00:01:35.366 --> 00:01:38.936
l don't drink. l don't smoke.
l don't do drugs.

22
00:01:40.066 --> 00:01:41.367
l play video games.

23
00:01:41.399 --> 00:01:44.569
which l think is far superior
an addiction

24
00:01:44.600 --> 00:01:45.801
than any of those other ones.

25
00:01:50.766 --> 00:01:52.601
l wanted to be a hero.

26
00:01:52.633 --> 00:01:54.701
l wanted to be the center
of attention.

27
00:01:54.733 --> 00:01:56.801
l wanted the glory.
l wanted the fame.

28
00:01:56.833 --> 00:01:58.267
l wanted the prem girls
come at me and say.

29
00:01:58.300 --> 00:02:00.335
''Hi. l see that you're good
at Centipede.''

30
00:02:02.833 --> 00:02:04.734
l had somebody draw
an analogy for me once

31
00:02:04.766 --> 00:02:06.734
that l always remembered.

32
00:02:06.766 --> 00:02:11.036
The top French pilot in World
War l shot down 24 enemy planes.

33
00:02:12.833 --> 00:02:15.802
The top American pilot--
you don't know his name. do you?

34
00:02:15.833 --> 00:02:18.635
Nobody does.
But it's Eddie Rickenbacker.

35
00:02:18.666 --> 00:02:21.769
Shot down 26 enemy planes.

36
00:02:21.799 --> 00:02:23.568
The German Ace. the Red Baron.

37
00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:25.535
Everyone knows
who the Red Baron is.

38
00:02:25.566 --> 00:02:29.236
That's 'cause he shot down
87 enemy planes.

39
00:02:29.266 --> 00:02:32.202
l mean. he was the best.

40
00:02:32.233 --> 00:02:36.804
There's just--There's a level
of difference between people.

41
00:02:36.833 --> 00:02:38.968
and it translates
into some games.

42
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.303
Donkey Hong and Pac-Man
and Ms. Pac-Man

43
00:02:51.333 --> 00:02:53.368
and Galaga and Defender.

44
00:02:53.400 --> 00:02:55.869
these are the games
that caught the public eye.

45
00:02:55.900 --> 00:02:58.669
These are the games
people cared about.

46
00:02:58.699 --> 00:03:02.670
And so if you wanna be known
as being world-class.

47
00:03:02.699 --> 00:03:04.101
you gotta master
one of those games.

48
00:03:04.133 --> 00:03:05.901
l like the simplicity of it.

49
00:03:05.933 --> 00:03:06.933
and that's what
you'll probably hear

50
00:03:06.966 --> 00:03:09.101
from a lot of people
that like retro games

51
00:03:09.133 --> 00:03:10.667
is that it's the simplicity.

52
00:03:10.699 --> 00:03:15.004
Those games challenge
eye-hand coordination.

53
00:03:15.033 --> 00:03:17.568
mind-body coordination.
fast reaction time.

54
00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:19.468
and comprehensive thinking.

55
00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:21.869
on a level
that modern games don't.

56
00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:25.503
Memorization and
pattern recognition is key.

57
00:03:25.533 --> 00:03:26.967
Because for you
to get a single point further

58
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.001
in an old game
from the early eighties

59
00:03:29.033 --> 00:03:30.734
meant a tremendous increase
of skill.

60
00:03:30.766 --> 00:03:33.068
lf you do not know
the next pattern coming up

61
00:03:33.100 --> 00:03:36.503
in a Tron light-cycle event.
you will lose your life.

62
00:03:36.533 --> 00:03:39.168
Only the die-hards
who. for some reason.

63
00:03:39.199 --> 00:03:42.469
really love those games.
continue to stick with them.

64
00:03:48.833 --> 00:03:51.602
But what we've done is had the
mayor tie off the entire street

65
00:03:51.633 --> 00:03:53.234
so that LiFe magazine
could come to town

66
00:03:53.266 --> 00:03:55.901
and photograph the world's
greatest video game players.

67
00:03:55.933 --> 00:03:56.933
who've been flown in

68
00:03:56.966 --> 00:04:00.169
especially for
this LiFe photographic session.

69
00:04:00.199 --> 00:04:02.602
All these great superstars
are coming from North Carolina.

70
00:04:02.633 --> 00:04:05.135
California. Canada.
many other places.

71
00:04:05.166 --> 00:04:08.202
to be photographed
as the official world champions

72
00:04:08.233 --> 00:04:09.601
on many different games.

73
00:04:11.199 --> 00:04:15.070
That was the first time
two world-class players

74
00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:18.203
went head-to-head for
a competition was LiFe magazine.

75
00:04:18.233 --> 00:04:19.601
_
Without a doubt
l met players

76
00:04:19.633 --> 00:04:21.868
that were amongst the best
in the world

77
00:04:21.900 --> 00:04:24.636
and maybe even would say
or do whatever they could

78
00:04:24.666 --> 00:04:27.235
to make people believe
they were the best in the world.

79
00:04:27.266 --> 00:04:28.634
Well. at that time.

80
00:04:28.666 --> 00:04:30.834
he was the world record holder
on Centipede.

81
00:04:30.866 --> 00:04:32.367
But also at that time.

82
00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:34.568
he was the world record holder
on Donkey Hong.

83
00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:36.435
But we didn't know that.
because someone else

84
00:04:36.466 --> 00:04:38.401
was invited there
from Hansas City

85
00:04:38.433 --> 00:04:40.902
who. because of a claim
they had made.

86
00:04:40.933 --> 00:04:44.903
it was presumed that they
were the Donkey Hong champion.

87
00:04:44.933 --> 00:04:48.469
Donkey Hong was the one
that l first lied about.

88
00:04:48.499 --> 00:04:50.635
But he had submitted
a bogus score.

89
00:04:50.666 --> 00:04:52.634
and l finally met him there
at LiFe magazine.

90
00:04:52.666 --> 00:04:54.901
and l finally sat down
to play him.

91
00:04:54.933 --> 00:04:57.669
We had not been there long.
and Bill said.

92
00:04:57.700 --> 00:04:59.902
''Come on. Let's play.''

93
00:05:01.333 --> 00:05:03.268
l went in the arcade
and sat down with Donkey Hong.

94
00:05:03.299 --> 00:05:05.268
and l beat him to a pulp.

95
00:05:05.299 --> 00:05:06.868
Well. l was better
than the best.

96
00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:09.669
And l got--
l got 200.OOO against Bill.

97
00:05:09.700 --> 00:05:13.170
Bill got 800.OOO
on his first man in that game.

98
00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:15.902
He shellacked me.
He shellacked me.

99
00:05:15.933 --> 00:05:18.635
Basically. he walked away
with his head down and humbled.

100
00:05:18.666 --> 00:05:20.367
and that brought him
to the truth.

101
00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:22.668
And from there.
we worked together.

102
00:05:24.866 --> 00:05:27.068
Well. the Bible--
Proverbs says.

103
00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:29.902
''As iron sharpens iron.
so one man sharpens another.''

104
00:05:29.933 --> 00:05:31.467
Bill made me a better person.

105
00:05:31.499 --> 00:05:37.539
and did so
by basically making me confess.

106
00:05:37.566 --> 00:05:40.635
l've pointed out to Steve
that he's the person he is today

107
00:05:40.666 --> 00:05:43.035
because he came under the wrath
of Bill Mitchell.

108
00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:47.402
ln front of the 19 top players
in the nation.

109
00:05:47.433 --> 00:05:48.901
actually North America.

110
00:05:48.933 --> 00:05:51.769
he did the highest
Donkey Hong score possible

111
00:05:51.799 --> 00:05:55.136
and also found out that the game
ends on the 22nd board.

112
00:06:23.433 --> 00:06:25.668
Since. l so-called
debuted on the scene

113
00:06:25.700 --> 00:06:28.169
at LiFe magazine in 1982.

114
00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:32.304
there hasn't been anybody
who's played even close.

115
00:06:32.333 --> 00:06:34.668
When Billy Mitchell
walks into an arcade.

116
00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:36.868
you know. everything stops.

117
00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:38.234
There's electricity
around Billy Mitchell.

118
00:06:38.266 --> 00:06:39.834
Everybody wants
to crowd around him.

119
00:06:39.866 --> 00:06:41.167
Everybody wants to see him.

120
00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:43.602
You know. everything about him
is perfect. you know?

121
00:06:43.633 --> 00:06:46.535
Billy is just that person.
You know. he wants to represent.

122
00:06:46.566 --> 00:06:47.733
lf you could hack
into the machine

123
00:06:47.766 --> 00:06:50.168
and program it to play itself.

124
00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:51.634
you couldn't
even program it that well.

125
00:06:51.666 --> 00:06:54.435
There's a glamour to Billy.
There's a specialness to Billy.

126
00:06:54.466 --> 00:06:57.168
He was the first. He was
the first great. great player.

127
00:06:57.200 --> 00:06:58.668
The fact of the matter is.

128
00:06:58.700 --> 00:07:03.404
Bill is the best classic
arcade gamer of our era.

129
00:07:03.433 --> 00:07:05.668
lt's actually carved
a part of my personality

130
00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:07.334
that benefits me every day.

131
00:07:07.366 --> 00:07:11.937
l mean. a burning passion
never to settle for what l have

132
00:07:11.966 --> 00:07:14.201
in my business. in my family.

133
00:07:14.233 --> 00:07:16.602
That's what competitive gaming
has done for me.

134
00:07:16.633 --> 00:07:18.368
He's a winner.

135
00:07:18.400 --> 00:07:19.968
Billy Mitchell
is absolutely a winner.

136
00:07:19.999 --> 00:07:22.969
lt's sort of like
being in a maze.

137
00:07:22.999 --> 00:07:26.236
but everything you see
is actually sauce.

138
00:07:26.266 --> 00:07:27.767
The all-around
most-seasoned person

139
00:07:27.799 --> 00:07:31.236
in the hot saucelchicken wing
industry--yeah. for sure. me.

140
00:07:31.666 --> 00:07:34.935
There's a production end of it.
There's the preparation.

141
00:07:34.966 --> 00:07:36.634
When there's the sales
end of it.

142
00:07:36.666 --> 00:07:39.301
there's not somebody
who encompasses

143
00:07:39.333 --> 00:07:41.134
all of those areas like me
that l've ever met.

144
00:07:41.166 --> 00:07:43.334
He sells his hot sauce.
he sells himself.

145
00:07:43.366 --> 00:07:47.236
Because he's so charming
and such a good ambassador

146
00:07:47.266 --> 00:07:49.501
for all gaming
because he's positive.

147
00:07:49.533 --> 00:07:50.834
there's no reason.
in my opinion.

148
00:07:50.866 --> 00:07:53.401
why Billy Mitchell couldn't end
up on a Wheaties box someday.

149
00:08:01.999 --> 00:08:05.169
The video arcade classic
has finally been conquered.

150
00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:07.468
On July 4.
at a New Hampshire arcade.

151
00:08:07.499 --> 00:08:10.903
34-year-old Billy Mitchell
became the first person

152
00:08:10.933 --> 00:08:15.137
to master Pac-Man by recording
the first ever perfect game.

153
00:08:15.166 --> 00:08:18.269
#  Billy Mitchell
primo joystick dude #

154
00:08:18.299 --> 00:08:21.936
#  Amazing in the maze.
he ain't gonna lose #

155
00:08:21.966 --> 00:08:24.001
To get through every board.
getting every dot.

156
00:08:24.033 --> 00:08:26.802
every energizer.
every ghost that's applicable.

157
00:08:26.833 --> 00:08:29.802
to reach to the final 256th
screen without dying?

158
00:08:29.833 --> 00:08:31.501
That's--lt's impressive
in its own right.

159
00:08:31.533 --> 00:08:33.201
The success of this
was not just because

160
00:08:33.233 --> 00:08:35.034
someone got
a perfect Pac-Man score.

161
00:08:35.066 --> 00:08:38.068
but because Billy Mitchell
got a perfect Pac-Man score.

162
00:08:38.100 --> 00:08:41.603
#  Blue man in the corridor
singing the blues #

163
00:08:41.633 --> 00:08:43.668
#  A perfect game goes down #

164
00:08:46.366 --> 00:08:49.469
#  Billy's on the move #

165
00:08:53.366 --> 00:08:56.936
lf l have all this good fortune.
if everything's rollin' my way.

166
00:08:56.966 --> 00:08:59.535
if all these balls
have bounced in my favor...

167
00:09:00.933 --> 00:09:02.534
there is some poor bastard
out there

168
00:09:02.566 --> 00:09:04.968
who's getting
the screws put to him.

169
00:09:16.733 --> 00:09:19.669
When l got laid off
and l had time on my hands.

170
00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:21.301
l was thinking.
''Well. what can l do

171
00:09:21.333 --> 00:09:25.136
''to kind of feel like
l have control of something.''

172
00:09:25.166 --> 00:09:29.169
so l looked at Twin Galaxies.

173
00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:32.336
l just--well. l typed in
Donkey Hong world record.

174
00:09:32.366 --> 00:09:36.303
and some spreadsheet came up.
and l saw what the score was.

175
00:09:36.333 --> 00:09:43.173
lt was held by Billy Mitchell.
and it was. like. 874.OOO.

176
00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:45.101
l go. ''Hey. l can beat that.''

177
00:09:49.166 --> 00:09:50.400
Almost there.

178
00:09:50.433 --> 00:09:52.234
l mean. l'm not the kind of wife
that's needy

179
00:09:52.266 --> 00:09:53.667
that l need him sitting on
the couch with me every night.

180
00:09:53.700 --> 00:09:54.700
l don't need that.

181
00:09:54.733 --> 00:09:57.068
What l need is him in the house
helping me with the kids

182
00:09:57.100 --> 00:09:58.734
or l need him
being with the kids.

183
00:09:58.766 --> 00:10:00.667
So he would want
to come out here and play.

184
00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:03.702
and that would drive me crazy.
'cause he is definitely OCD.

185
00:10:03.733 --> 00:10:05.201
When he is obsessed
on something.

186
00:10:05.233 --> 00:10:07.935
he is so focused.
and l have to be like. ''Hello.''

187
00:10:07.966 --> 00:10:11.169
Um. so then l just said.
''You have to do it at night.''

188
00:10:15.666 --> 00:10:17.634
ls level 2 easy?

189
00:10:20.233 --> 00:10:22.034
Yeah. it's prem easy.

190
00:10:23.833 --> 00:10:28.170
l've dreamed of. you know.
being a musician for a living.

191
00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:29.434
That's what my dream was.

192
00:10:29.466 --> 00:10:32.101
He was brought up to be
that he was smart.

193
00:10:32.133 --> 00:10:33.868
he was an athlete.
he was talented.

194
00:10:33.899 --> 00:10:37.803
and for whatever reason.
he could never get those to fit.

195
00:10:43.933 --> 00:10:48.337
Steve was one of the original
starving grunge bands

196
00:10:48.366 --> 00:10:50.167
here in Seattle.
just starving.

197
00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:53.236
The only people who came
to see him was us.

198
00:10:53.266 --> 00:10:55.001
With his music.
it's almost like

199
00:10:55.033 --> 00:10:57.268
he didn't want people to know
he was doing it.

200
00:10:57.300 --> 00:10:59.535
He's a total paradox that way.

201
00:10:59.566 --> 00:11:04.904
#  l've been looking so long
at these pictures of you #

202
00:11:04.933 --> 00:11:07.702
He has maybe a little social
hang-ups here and there

203
00:11:07.733 --> 00:11:10.402
that. um--
that haven't allowed him

204
00:11:10.433 --> 00:11:12.835
to be as successful
on one end as in other ends.

205
00:11:13.566 --> 00:11:18.537
They got to the state finals.
and Steve couldn't pitch.

206
00:11:18.566 --> 00:11:20.601
l've probably seen Steve
with tears in his eyes

207
00:11:20.633 --> 00:11:22.001
more than any other guy l know.

208
00:11:22.033 --> 00:11:24.668
uh. because of the frustration
that would build in him.

209
00:11:24.700 --> 00:11:26.134
And half the time.
it was on the pitcher's mound.

210
00:11:26.700 --> 00:11:29.569
He had hurt his arm.
l had pitched him too much.

211
00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:32.302
l was the manager of the team.

212
00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:36.836
lt was a chance for him to shine
in front of thousands of people.

213
00:11:36.866 --> 00:11:39.868
That killed him--
that he couldn't pitch

214
00:11:39.899 --> 00:11:42.602
because it's that
competitiveness in him.

215
00:11:43.800 --> 00:11:47.170
#  And we kissed
as the sky fell in #

216
00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:49.368
#  Holding you close #

217
00:11:49.399 --> 00:11:51.835
#  How l always held close #

218
00:11:51.866 --> 00:11:57.805
l envisioned him
as. uh. an engineer at Boeing.

219
00:11:58.866 --> 00:12:02.402
My dad worked at Boeing
for 30 some years.

220
00:12:02.433 --> 00:12:05.536
and the plan was to go to Boeing
and be a lifer.

221
00:12:05.566 --> 00:12:07.067
as they call 'em.

222
00:12:07.100 --> 00:12:08.501
But. um. things didn't work out.

223
00:12:08.533 --> 00:12:10.101
l don't know if he told you
that he was laid off

224
00:12:10.133 --> 00:12:12.335
the day we signed papers
on our house. Yeah.

225
00:12:12.366 --> 00:12:14.434
#  And you finally found #

226
00:12:14.466 --> 00:12:19.270
#  All your courage
to let it all go #

227
00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:26.235
He never has quite reached
that pinnacle.

228
00:12:26.266 --> 00:12:28.801
He never quite.
in any of his endeavors.

229
00:12:28.833 --> 00:12:31.936
was regaled
as the number-one guy.

230
00:12:31.966 --> 00:12:34.134
the guy that was better
than the rest

231
00:12:34.166 --> 00:12:36.001
and was on top of the mountain.

232
00:12:36.033 --> 00:12:38.168
Oh. he's just come up short
in a lot of things in his life.

233
00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:40.936
and l just think. you know.

234
00:12:40.966 --> 00:12:42.934
nobody wants to do that
all the time.

235
00:12:42.966 --> 00:12:45.101
#  Lost in the cold #

236
00:12:45.133 --> 00:12:50.905
#  You were always so lost
in the dark #

237
00:12:50.933 --> 00:12:53.402
#  Remembering you #

238
00:12:53.433 --> 00:12:56.669
lt has my high score saved
on there from last.

239
00:12:56.700 --> 00:12:59.235
#  Slow drowned.
you were angels #

240
00:12:59.266 --> 00:13:02.369
#  So much more than everything #

241
00:13:02.399 --> 00:13:04.735
#  Hold for the last time #

242
00:13:04.766 --> 00:13:07.668
#  Then slip away quietly #

243
00:13:07.700 --> 00:13:10.369
What plunged me
into competitive gaming.

244
00:13:10.399 --> 00:13:13.836
never to come out.
was Donkey Hong.

245
00:13:13.866 --> 00:13:17.236
Donkey Hong. Well. that was
the first ever Mario game.

246
00:13:17.266 --> 00:13:19.368
The whole thing
is a construction site.

247
00:13:19.399 --> 00:13:21.401
lt's all these girders
and elevators with ladders

248
00:13:21.433 --> 00:13:23.168
going from one girder
to the next.

249
00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:26.770
The whole goal. the whole time
is to get past the obstacles

250
00:13:26.800 --> 00:13:30.637
that Hong is throwing at you
and get--get the girl.

251
00:13:30.666 --> 00:13:33.468
Well. Donkey Hong. without
question. is the hardest game.

252
00:13:33.499 --> 00:13:36.402
lt's ridiculously difficult
on the first screen.

253
00:13:38.266 --> 00:13:40.701
Donkey Hong
is releasing these barrels.

254
00:13:40.733 --> 00:13:42.101
You got to jump
over the barrels.

255
00:13:42.133 --> 00:13:43.300
You gotta duck
the barrels.

256
00:13:43.333 --> 00:13:46.969
You can grab a hammer
and hammer the barrels.

257
00:13:46.999 --> 00:13:49.669
Okay. the secret
about the barrel board

258
00:13:49.700 --> 00:13:52.002
is you can actually
control the barrels.

259
00:13:52.033 --> 00:13:53.768
Right above this ladder.

260
00:13:53.800 --> 00:13:56.135
you'll do a quick left.
and then a hard right turn.

261
00:13:56.166 --> 00:13:58.868
See how it went down?
Went down again.

262
00:13:58.899 --> 00:14:01.168
You gotta get past
all the barrels. the fireballs.

263
00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:02.200
get up the ladders.

264
00:14:02.233 --> 00:14:04.201
And as soon as you get to her.

265
00:14:04.233 --> 00:14:06.868
Donkey Hong takes her away
to the next level.

266
00:14:09.833 --> 00:14:12.302
The average Donkey Hong game
doesn't last a minute.

267
00:14:12.333 --> 00:14:14.134
lt's absolute brutality.

268
00:14:14.166 --> 00:14:16.134
Each of the 18 elevator boards

269
00:14:16.166 --> 00:14:19.335
represents the greatest
challenge in video game playing.

270
00:14:19.366 --> 00:14:21.334
The average gamer on Donkey Hong

271
00:14:21.366 --> 00:14:24.802
will never get past
the third elevator stage.

272
00:14:24.833 --> 00:14:27.435
Just the slightest touch from
one of these springs. kills you.

273
00:14:27.466 --> 00:14:30.268
There's no hammer for them.
There's no way to defeat them.

274
00:14:30.300 --> 00:14:32.702
All you can do is avoid them.
That's it.

275
00:14:32.733 --> 00:14:34.568
And the secret
to the third elevators

276
00:14:34.600 --> 00:14:38.337
is knowing which spring
to go on.

277
00:14:38.366 --> 00:14:41.001
and then knowing which spring
to move up the ladder on.

278
00:14:41.033 --> 00:14:43.502
and recognizing
when you must retreat.

279
00:14:43.533 --> 00:14:46.802
lf you don't time it just
exactly right. you will die.

280
00:14:46.833 --> 00:14:50.436
lt boils down
to hardcore skill.

281
00:14:50.466 --> 00:14:53.702
So l go on that one because it
line up with the dashed line.

282
00:14:53.733 --> 00:14:57.303
Now l'm waiting for one to line
up with the solid line there.

283
00:14:58.466 --> 00:15:00.801
l have said from the day
l met Steve

284
00:15:00.833 --> 00:15:03.702
that his talent
is in his hands.

285
00:15:03.733 --> 00:15:06.035
He pitched.
He was at basketball.

286
00:15:06.066 --> 00:15:07.634
He's a phenomenal drawer.

287
00:15:07.666 --> 00:15:09.434
and if you ever seen
pictures that he's drawn.

288
00:15:09.466 --> 00:15:11.668
but he's very artistic.

289
00:15:11.700 --> 00:15:14.035
lt's operating on some
subconscious level with him.

290
00:15:14.066 --> 00:15:15.500
l think.

291
00:15:15.533 --> 00:15:19.270
When we were driving to Hansas
or whatever. family trips.

292
00:15:19.300 --> 00:15:21.101
he'd sit there.
and for a hundred miles

293
00:15:21.133 --> 00:15:23.735
would bang his head. you know.

294
00:15:23.766 --> 00:15:25.968
four--four time
against the back of the seat.

295
00:15:26.399 --> 00:15:29.136
Five. six. seven. eight. nine...

296
00:15:29.166 --> 00:15:31.535
Well. l've often thought that
he maybe is a little autistic.

297
00:15:31.566 --> 00:15:33.901
that he's just
that obsessive compulsive.

298
00:15:33.933 --> 00:15:36.201
'cause he would get
something in his mind.

299
00:15:36.233 --> 00:15:37.801
He wanted to play drums.

300
00:15:37.833 --> 00:15:39.768
and l don't even know
where he got that idea.

301
00:15:39.800 --> 00:15:45.639
This is Derek's drum set.
and it's not too bad.

302
00:15:45.666 --> 00:15:48.835
lt's--lt does the trick.

303
00:16:26.300 --> 00:16:31.571
The actual game play involves
so much eye-hand coordination.

304
00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:32.901
mind-body coordination.

305
00:16:32.933 --> 00:16:35.735
fast reaction time.
and comprehensive thinking.

306
00:16:35.766 --> 00:16:38.568
Such a high level
of precise execution.

307
00:16:39.700 --> 00:16:40.834
So much skill...

308
00:16:42.366 --> 00:16:44.234
involves so much learning.

309
00:16:48.433 --> 00:16:53.404
You have to have
deep comprehensive intelligence.

310
00:16:56.633 --> 00:16:58.868
Um. for years and years.
it was believed

311
00:16:58.899 --> 00:17:02.970
that Billy's record of 874.OOO
in 1982

312
00:17:02.999 --> 00:17:05.369
was really the highest score
anyone would ever get.

313
00:17:05.399 --> 00:17:07.668
And in fact. some of us
have played this game

314
00:17:07.699 --> 00:17:09.968
every day or every week
or every month since then.

315
00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:11.267
and no one's
gotten close to that.

316
00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:14.302
No one across
that big length of time

317
00:17:14.333 --> 00:17:18.370
will ever be able to beat
his world record.

